<topic id="d1e59"><title>Exercise 1.8</title><body><p>
<b>For what values can you define the inverse of the function
<d4p_eqn_inline>
    <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>cos</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>sin</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
  </d4p_eqn_inline>. (Hint: set
<d4p_eqn_inline>
    <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>f</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>cos</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>sin</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
  </d4p_eqn_inline> look at its inverse and figure out the answer.)</b>
</p><p>
Solution:
</p><p>
The inverse function 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mi>f</m:mi></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
, with 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>f</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>cos</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>sin</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
 can be defined at any argument that is a value for 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>cos</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>sin</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
. Since 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>sin</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
 takes values between -1 and 1, and cosine is an even function, its values lie between 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>cos</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
 (which is 1) and 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>cos</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
, which is .540302306, more or less. Therefore this inverse function can be defined between this value and 1. In that domain its value must be chosen to be one from among the various arguments for 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>cos</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mo stretchy="false">(</m:mo><m:mi>sin</m:mi><m:mo>⁡</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
 which have that value. (for example, you could choose a value between 0 and 
<d4p_eqn_inline>
  <mathml><m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mi>π</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:math></mathml>
</d4p_eqn_inline>
.)
</p><p>
